1 Introduction

QOD is a class aimed at checking and exploring the Quality of the Data in the Event Log. This class provides methods for visual and numerical inspection to also support a first Decriptive Statistics. It works loading an object obtained with the dataLoader::getData() method: this means that an Event Log must be previously loaded via a dataLoader object.

1.1 Data Loading

Lets consider the following CSV, containing the Event Log we might want to load:

ID Event Date Sex
1 Medical Visit 2001-01-04 M
1 Imaging 2001-01-11 M
1 Imaging 2001-01-16 M
1 Imaging 2001-01-19 M
1 Medical Visit 2001-01-21 M
1 Imaging 2001-01-31 M
1 Biopsy 2001-02-08 M
1 partial resection 2001-02-12 M
1 death 2001-02-17 M
2 Imaging 2001-01-09 M
2 Imaging 2001-01-14 M
2 Imaging 2001-01-19 M
2 Imaging 2001-01-27 M
2 Medical Visit 2001-02-05 M
2 Medical Visit 2001-02-07 M

On first we have to load the Event Log with a dataLoder object:

objDL <- dataLoader(verbose.mode = FALSE)
objDL$load.csv(nomeFile = "../dataS/four.generated.csv",sep = ";",IDName = "ID",EVENTName = "Event",dateColumnName = "Date",format.column.date = "%Y-%m-%d")
objDL.out <- objDL$getData()

then, the stucture returned by the dataLoader::getData() class can given in input to the QOD instance:

objQOD <- QOD()
objQOD$loadDataset(dataList = objDL$getData())

In the current version of pMineR, QOD exposes the following methods:

  • QOD::query() : to query the Event Log;

  • QOD::eventHeatmap() : to plot the so called Event Heatmap, a map to show how often an event appear after another event in a graphical way.

  • QOD::plotTimeline() : to graphically show the behaviour of a set of traces.

1.2 Querying the Event Log

The QOD::query() method is a practical tools to scout which traces satisfy some rules.

For example, to get all the ID of the patients passing from the Event Biopsy and then death (in an arbitrary number of steps) we can use tee syntax:

arr.ID <- objQOD$query(from = "Biopsy",to = "death")

If we want to see how many flies between the two nodes in less than one month:

arr.ID <- objQOD$query(from = "Biopsy",to = "death",time.range = c(0,31),UM = "days")

The to parameter also permits the use of the wildcard , this means any event*. So, for example, the following query reveals all the Biopsy where the next event (whichever it was) happened between the 10th and the 20th day:

arr.ID <- objQOD$query(from = "Biopsy",to = "*",time.range = c(10,20),UM = "days")

we can also reason in terms of number of jumps and ask for the patients passing through the two events in a number of jump ranged between 4 and 8:

arr.ID <- objQOD$query(from = "Biopsy",to = "death",step.range = c(4,8) )

Here there is the list of the possible parameters:

  • from : the event to start from. It can also be BEGIN.

  • to : the target event. It can also be END

  • complement : the default value is FALSE. If set to TRUE, instaed of returning the ID of the patients satisfying the query, it return the one who do not satisfy the query.

  • time.range : is a two-element array containing the time window where a transition between from and to should be considered valid. The default value is c(0,Inf).

  • step.range : is a two-element array containing the number of transitions between from and to, to consider the trace valid. The default value is c(0,Inf).

  • UM : is the Unity of Measure. It can be minutes,hours, days, weeks, months. The default value is the value specified with the creation of the object QOD; if no unity of measure is passed, minutes is considered as a default.

  • arr.passingThrough : contains an array of events which should be in between the from and to. The order is not important: c(A,B) or C(B,A) are equivalent.

  • arr.NOTpassingThrough : contains an array of events which should NOT be in between the from and to. Again, the order is not important.

  • returnCompleteMatrix : By default this parameter is set to FALSE and only the array of the patients ID is returned. If the user wants to dig into the data and see more in details which couples from - to has been checked, switching this parameter to TRUE will return a more detailed matrix. The output for the patient moving from Biopsy (from) to death (to) within 14 days, will return the following result:

mtr.ID <- objQOD$query(from = "Biopsy",to = "death", time.range = c(0,14), UM = "days", returnCompleteMatrix = TRUE )

mtr.ID%>%
  kbl() %>%
  kable_minimal()
from to step time valid
1 7 9 2 9 1
16 6 8 2 10 1
18 4 6 2 13 1
21 7 9 2 8 1
38 4 6 2 5 1
40 4 5 1 1 1
46 7 9 2 2 1
60 5 7 2 10 1
63 6 10 4 11 1
68 4 5 1 3 1
75 4 6 2 13 1
85 5 7 2 10 1
87 3 4 1 3 1
88 5 6 1 1 1
9 4 6 2 13 1
96 7 9 2 4 1

where the first column contains the Patients ID, the second the position in the trace of the from Event, the third the position of the to Event, the colump step indicated the distance in terms of event, the column time the distance in terms of days (as specified in the UM) and valid indicates that this record satisfy the query.

1.3 HeatMap

This map plots how often (relative numners) from an Event we can move to another, in the traces of the Event Log. For example, in the following HeatMap:

objQOD$eventHeatmap(cex =0.8)

we can observe that in the 56% of the cases, after a Biopsy we have (in one or more steps) a partial resection. If we are intersted in focusing the attention on specific window of %, we can specify the window setting the lower of the upper bound :

objQOD$eventHeatmap(cex =0.8,threshold.low = 0.40,threshold.hi = 0.80  )

the parameters cex, show.diagonal and par.margin and meant for graphical use and specify respectively: the font size, the presence of not of numbers in the diagonal and the margins of the image.

1.4 Plotting a cohort of timelines

To graphically represent one or more timeline, also deciding which events should be plotted, the methods QOD::plotTimeline() can be used. In the following example, the entire cohort is plotted, scaling the x-axes in months, and the death and Biopsy events are plotted with a pch equal to 17 and 19 respectively:

objQOD$plotTimeline(objDL.obj = objDL.out,UM = "months",ID.on.y.label = FALSE,arr.evt.pch = c("Biopsy"=19,"death"=17))

Note: the parameter objDL.out is optional: if not specified, QOD::plotTimeline() will use the data previously loaded with the class QOD::loadDataset().

We can also plot a limited set of patients, showing the IDs. In the following case we limited the plot, changed the ordering and repositioned the legend.

arr.IPP.to.plot <- names(objDL.out$pat.process)[1:10]
objQOD$plotTimeline(objDL.obj = objDL.out,arr.ID = arr.IPP.to.plot, UM = "months",ID.on.y.label = TRUE,arr.evt.pch = c("Biopsy"=19,"death"=17),ID.ordering = TRUE,ID.ordering.desc = FALSE,legend.Pos = "bottomright")

If we are interested in observing only the first week, we can specify the max.time parameter.

arr.IPP.to.plot <- names(objDL.out$pat.process)[1:10]
objQOD$plotTimeline(objDL.obj = objDL.out,arr.ID = arr.IPP.to.plot, UM = "months",ID.on.y.label = TRUE,arr.evt.pch = c("Biopsy"=19,"death"=17),ID.ordering = TRUE,ID.ordering.desc = FALSE,legend.Pos = "bottomright",max.time = 7)

And to avoid a chaotic situation of markers we can also limit the dot to a subset of Events, for example Biopsy,partial resection and death:

arr.IPP.to.plot <- names(objDL.out$pat.process)[10:20]
objQOD$plotTimeline(objDL.obj = objDL.out, arr.events = c("Biopsy","partial resection","death"), arr.ID = arr.IPP.to.plot, UM = "months",ID.on.y.label = TRUE,arr.evt.pch = c("Biopsy"=19,"death"=17,"partial resection"=15),max.time = 14)

The admitted parameters are the following:

  • objDL.obj : is the output of the method dataLoader::getData(). This is optional: if not specified, the method will use what previously loaded with the method QOD:loadDataset().

  • arr.ID : if specified it contains the set of Patients ID to plot. The default is c() and means all

  • max.time : is the max time to window the x-axes.

  • UM : the unit of measure. It cna be minutes, hours, days, weeks, months

  • arr.events : is the set of events to plot. The default is c() which means "all*

  • arr.evt.pch : by default the events are plotted with a pch equal to 3 or the one indicated in the evt.pch.default.value parameter. In this array the user can associate one or more event to a specific pch. The array names are the event names and the values are the wished pchs.

  • evt.pch.default.value : is the pch which should be used by default for all the events

  • ID.on.y.label : can be TRUE or FALSE. If set to TRUE the IDs will be plotted, for each trace, on the left

  • y.label.cex : the cex for the y-axes

  • Time.on.x.label : if TRUE it shows the time on the x-axes.

  • x.label.cex : the cex for the x-axes

  • plot.legend : it can be TRUE or FALSE and permits to plot the legend, in a desided position

  • legend.Pos : it permits to posiiton the legend.

  • legend.cex : the cex for the legend

  • ID.ordering : if set to TRUE (default) permits to order the traces from the shortest to the longest or vice versa;

  • ID.ordering.desc : if ID.ordering is set to TRUE, this parameter can be set to TRUE to have a descending or to FALSE for an ascending ordering of the traces.

1.5 Plotting the aligned traces

The method QOD::plotTraceEvolution permits to plot the traces, aligned, and reveal the contribute of all the traces during the time.

objQOD$plotTraceEvolution(objDL.out = objDL.out,UM = "weeks")

we also might want to see the cumulative, maybe for death and Biopsy only:

objQOD$plotTraceEvolution(objDL.out = objDL.out,UM = "weeks",cumulative = TRUE,arr.events = c("death","Biopsy"))

In some cases, the events in the Event Log can refer to persiting events during the time. Lets condider the following example:

ID Event Date Sex
1 Hospitalisation 2001-01-04 M
1 Home 2001-01-11 M
1 Hospitalisation 2001-01-16 M
1 Home 2001-01-19 M
1 death 2001-02-17 M
2 Hospitalisation 2001-01-09 M
2 Home 2001-01-14 M
3 Hospitalisation 2001-01-09 F
3 Home 2001-01-18 F
3 Hospitalisation 2001-01-21 F
3 ICU 2001-01-31 F
3 death 2001-02-07 F
4 Home 2001-01-08 F
4 Hospitalisation 2001-01-22 F
4 Home 2001-01-23 F

Here, each event implicitly persist before the next: e.g.the first line means that the patient #1 has been ospitalized the 2001-01-19 and then sent back home the 2001-02-17. Between the 2001-01-19 and 2001-02-17 he was in the state Hospitalisation. So, if an event is not referred to a time point but might be referred to a state, the previous graphs can be better representative setting the parameter ** holdEvts ** to TRUE. This will count all the events until the next event will happen, representing how the states are activated during the time. Lets consider the previously mentioned csv and lets load it in a dataLoader obj:

newDLobj <- dataLoader(verbose.mode = FALSE)
newDLobj$load.csv(nomeFile = "../dataS/five.generated.csv",sep = ";",IDName = "ID",EVENTName = "Event",dateColumnName = "Date",format.column.date = "%Y-%m-%d")

we can avoid to create a new QOD class by passing the newDLobj::getData() into the input parameter objDL.out, in the method QOD::plotTraceEvolution():

objQOD$plotTraceEvolution(objDL.out = newDLobj$getData(),holdEvts = TRUE,UM = "days",max.t = 90)

this means that at time 0 almost the 60% of the patient was at home while the 40% was hospitalised. At the 60th day, for example, more than hte 20% of the patients was dead, the 30% of the patients was still hospitalised, a small amount of them was in ICU (7-9%?) and more than the 40% was hospitalized.

So, the holdEvts set to TRUE propagate ahead the state of an event and allow us to consider it as a state that will change when the next event will happen.
